# Strict TypeScript And ESLint Discipline

- Use strict TypeScript typing in all new/updated code.
- Avoid `any`; prefer explicit types, unions, generics, or `unknown` with narrowing.
- Avoid unsafe casts unless there is a clear runtime guarantee and comment.
- Do not disable ESLint rules inline, file-wide, or in config for convenience.
- Do not use `// @ts-ignore`; fix typing issues at the source.

## Examples

```ts
// BAD
// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any
const normalize = (value: any) => value;

// GOOD
const normalize = (value: string | number): string => String(value);
```
